1.2 Key Findings
The organization was compromised by the Akira ransomware group in a sophisticated, multi-stage attack spanning approximately 20 days. The threat actor leveraged a pre-staged remote access tool (AnyDesk) from a prior intrusion — consistent with a 'broker' resale model — to re-enter the environment. Key findings are as follows:
 
•       Initial Access: AnyDesk.exe was pre-staged in C:\Users\Public\ on AS-PC2 and used from external IP 88.97.164.155 to establish unauthorized remote access under the compromised account david.mitchell.
•       Credential Theft: The attacker enumerated LSASS via 'tasklist | findstr lsass' and accessed the named pipe \\Device\\NamedPipe\\lsass to steal credentials.
•       Defense Evasion: Security controls were disabled via kill.bat and a direct registry modification (DisableAntiSpyware = 1) at 21:03:42 on January 19, 2026.
•       C2 Beacon: A custom beacon (wsync.exe) was deployed to C:\ProgramData\ and communicated with two C2 servers at 104.21.30.237 and 172.67.174.46 via cdn.cloud-endpoint.net.
•       Lateral Movement: The attacker moved from AS-PC2 to AS-SRV using the as.srv.administrator account after network scanning with Advanced IP Scanner.
•       Data Exfiltration: Data was compressed into exfil_data.zip using st.exe on AS-SRV and exfiltrated prior to encryption, constituting a double-extortion attack.
•       Ransomware Deployment: The Akira ransomware binary (updater.exe) was staged on AS-SRV via PowerShell and executed at 22:18:33 on January 27, 2026. VSS shadow copies were deleted to prevent recovery.
•       Anti-Forensics: clean.bat was executed post-encryption to delete the ransomware binary.
 1.3 Immediate Actions Taken
•       Isolation of compromised hosts AS-PC2 and AS-SRV from the network.
•       Revocation of david.mitchell and as.srv.administrator account credentials.
•       Engagement of threat intelligence to correlate Akira IoCs with known campaign artifacts.
•       Blocking of all identified C2 domains and IP addresses at the perimeter firewall.
•       Preservation of forensic evidence (memory dumps, disk images, KQL query results) for legal and insurance purposes.
 1.4 Stakeholder Impact
•       Business operations on AS-SRV (primary server) disrupted due to full file encryption with .akira extension.
•       Potential exfiltration of sensitive corporate data via exfil_data.zip — extent of data loss under investigation.
•       Negotiation portal identified on TOR network: akiral2iz6a7qgd3ayp3l6yub7xx2uep76idk3u2kollpj5z3z636bad.onion.
•       Financial exposure from ransom demand, regulatory fines, and reputational risk is being assessed by legal and finance teams. 


