SECTION 6: RESPONSE & RECOVERY

 6.1 Immediate Containment Actions
•       Network isolation of AS-PC2 and AS-SRV — removed from production VLAN.
•       Disabled accounts: david.mitchell and as.srv.administrator across all domain controllers.
•       Firewall rules added blocking 104.21.30.237, 172.67.174.46, 88.97.164.155, cloud-endpoint.net.
•       AnyDesk blocked at endpoint and perimeter level.
 
6.2 Eradication Steps
•       Kill.bat, wsync.exe, scan.exe, st.exe, and updater.exe must be hunted across all endpoints — not only confirmed compromised hosts.
•       Registry key HKLM\...\Windows Defender\DisableAntiSpyware must be set back to 0 and verified post-reboot.
•       Full reimaging of AS-PC2 and AS-SRV recommended — do not attempt in-place recovery due to persistence mechanisms.
•       Audit all accounts for privilege escalation post-credential theft. Rotate ALL credentials environment-wide.
 
6.3 Recovery Steps
•       Validate backup integrity for AS-SRV before restoration — confirm backups pre-date January 7, 2026.
•       If no pre-compromise backups are available, legal must assess negotiation options and data recovery feasibility.
•       Re-deploy AS-SRV from a clean image once environment is declared threat-free.
•       Monitor for reinfection — Akira is known to re-enter environments via overlooked persistence mechanisms.
 
6.4 Post-Incident Monitoring
•       Deploy enhanced EDR telemetry with named pipe monitoring, registry write auditing, and LSASS access alerting.
•       Implement network-level detection for known cloud-endpoint.net domains and newly observed TLDs (.tech, .site, .top, .xyz).
•       Add SHA256 hashes from Section 4.1 to EDR block-list and SIEM alerting rules.
•       Hunt for additional staging artifacts using KQL queries provided in Appendix A.

 
SECTION 7: RECOMMENDATIONS

 
7.1 Immediate (0-7 Days)
•       Mandatory enterprise-wide credential rotation — all accounts must be considered compromised.
•       Deploy MFA on all remote access, VPN, and RDP entry points — AnyDesk and similar RMM tools must require MFA.
•       Implement application allowlisting to prevent execution of unsigned binaries from AppData, ProgramData, and Public directories.
•       Conduct threat hunt across all endpoints for IoCs listed in Section 4. 
7.2 Short-Term (7-30 Days)
•       Implement Privileged Access Workstations (PAW) for all administrator accounts to prevent lateral movement using harvested credentials.
•       Enforce LSASS Protection (RunAsPPL) via Group Policy to prevent credential dumping via named pipe.
•       Restrict bitsadmin and PowerShell Invoke-WebRequest to approved hosts/users only via AppLocker or WDAC.
•       Deploy honeypot accounts and shares to detect future lateral movement attempts.
 7.3 Strategic (30-90 Days)
•       Evaluate Zero Trust Architecture — lateral movement from PC2 to SRV relied on flat network topology with shared credentials.
•       Conduct a formal tabletop exercise simulating a ransomware attack using the Akira TTPs documented in this report.
•       Establish an immutable, air-gapped backup solution — VSS alone is insufficient against modern ransomware.
•       Join an ISAC relevant to your sector for Akira IoC sharing and advance warning of future campaigns.






